{"add":{"doc":{"id":"e688a04de91ab58a0d95ab999c399dfe8076db6b69202153d8932657c58fead8","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c1/Ravi_Shankar_2009_crop.jpg/170px-Ravi_Shankar_2009_crop.jpg","previous":[],"after":["During the Beatles' American tour in August 1965, Harrison's friend David Crosby of the Byrds introduced him to Indian classical music and the work of sitar maestro Ravi Shankar.[267][268] Harrison described Shankar as \"the first person who ever impressed me in my life ... and he was the only person who didn't try to impress me.\"[269] Harrison became fascinated with the sitar and immersed himself in Indian music.[270] According to Lavezzoli, Harrison's introduction of the instrument on the Beatles' song \"Norwegian Wood\" \"opened the floodgates for Indian instrumentation in rock music, triggering what Shankar would call 'The Great Sitar Explosion' of 1966–67\".[271] Lavezzoli described Harrison as \"the man most responsible for this phenomenon\".[272][nb 19]"]}}}